    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_582830142" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/582830142" />
    <a title="Harry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7597429-harry"><img alt="Harry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380595404p2/7597429.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/582830142?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Harry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Harry" href="/user/show/7597429-harry">Harry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7597429-harry?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer582830142" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12718401428131938421">This is not a novel I would compliment for it&apos;s stylistic prose, its character development, or it&apos;s originality in terms of plot: this is a novel that were it to be true is nothing short of a devastating indictment of the War on drugs. My rating of this book is based on its subject matter and its research and how it affects me as a reader.<br/><br/>Normally, I throw up my eyebrows in quizzical fashion when reading reviews that complain about the lack of verisimilitude, or that the author somehow has inven</span>
  <span id="freeText12718401428131938421" style="display:none">This is not a novel I would compliment for it's stylistic prose, its character development, or it's originality in terms of plot: this is a novel that were it to be true is nothing short of a devastating indictment of the War on drugs. My rating of this book is based on its subject matter and its research and how it affects me as a reader.<br /><br />Normally, I throw up my eyebrows in quizzical fashion when reading reviews that complain about the lack of verisimilitude, or that the author somehow has invented something in the reader's hometown that isn't true and therefore the whole novel is to be ridiculed and cast aside. It's fiction, the stuff's made up, folks! If you want realism, all the facts checked, then view your favorite documentary, or news column (not that facts are checked in the news), or gain your verisimilitude from reality TV! The beauty in art, as well as fiction, is that the author presents a view that is NOT as the world is. So, get over it.<br /><br />Having said that, if this novel's painstaking research is any indication (last count, the author spent 6 years doing research to pull this one off - that's 2,190 days) then what you will read will floor you. I say this if even a fraction of it is true. So, though fictionalized competently if not expertly, this book is about reality.<br /><br />Some reviewers call it Winslow's best, some his second best: with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8008928.Savages__Savages___1_" title="Savages (Savages, #1) by Don Winslow" rel="nofollow noopener">Savages</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/164760.The_Winter_of_Frankie_Machine" title="The Winter of Frankie Machine by Don Winslow" rel="nofollow noopener">The Winter of Frankie Machine</a> as the contenders. For myself, coming to this second Winslow book after reading the first in the Neal Carey series: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/243362.A_Cool_Breeze_on_the_Underground__Neal_Carey__1_" title="A Cool Breeze on the Underground (Neal Carey #1) by Don Winslow" rel="nofollow noopener">A Cool Breeze on the Underground</a> I can easily declare <i>The Power of the Dog</i> to be his best. With over 520 pages, it far surpasses the only other book I've read of Winslow's.<br /><br />So, I'm not going to talk about prose, setting, or the book's stylistic shortcomings. It's useless. Winslow has me in a corner because the subject matter is so devastating that it commands our attention every step of the way. The only thing to discuss is the veracity of what this novel is about and our opinion as readers of that truth. And if there's praise to be gifted to this novelist, than that praise belongs to Winslow for allowing us to see the consequences of the War on Drugs as seen through the eyes of the innocent and the not-so-innocent: the 3 or 4 fictional characters we follow across 3 decades.<br /><br />What is a War on Drugs? What is war? This is what I got from the book:<br /><br />War should be understood as <i>political violence</i>. We are obviously not actually waging a war on drugs. Drugs can't wage war. Drugs sit in plastic wrapping, or in a crack pipe. Ok. so who, then? Who or what are we waging war against? And why don't we call this war for what it really is? A political cold war that never ends. A war where the proliferation of hard drugs in our streets is the last thing of consequence. Drugs equals money, and money finances political violence. That is what Winslow tells me. <br /><br />But the collateral damage! I've heard that...that every war has them. But there's a difference between collateral damage that can't be avoided, and pure brutality for the sake of brutality. I find it horrific. <br /><br />This book is about sociopaths and psychopaths in power... what they will do to keep an idea away from this border while working for the U.S. government and against it. Winslow proves to us that ethics is only possible if you have a choice: faced with violence there is no such thing as ethics. There is a line between collateral damage and terrorism; and that line is drawn for the reader. And it is who steps across that line that floors you.<br /><br />And, so I think it's in this epic span of 3 decades, within this collateral damage that Winslow finds a chilling home for his novel and it's main characters. <br /><br />Fascinating book...I thought. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12718401428131938421" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


